<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-samplingdists" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Sampling Distribution of the Mean</title>
    <p>
        To understand how sample statistics vary, consider repeatedly drawing random samples of the same size from a population. 
        Suppose that each sample consists of <m>N=5</m> individuals and that the sample mean is calculated for every sample. 
        Because each sample is different, the sample mean is also likely to differ from one sample to another.
    </p>

    <p>
        Table <xref ref="tab-replications"/> shows the results of ten independent samples, each containing five observations. 
        Although every sample is drawn from the same population, the sample means are not identical because of random sampling variation.
    </p>

    <table xml:id="tab-replications">
        <title>Ten independent samples, each with a sample size of <m>N=5</m>.</title>
        <tabular>
            <row header="yes">
                <cell></cell>
                <cell>Person 1</cell>
                <cell>Person 2</cell>
                <cell>Person 3</cell>
                <cell>Person 4</cell>
                <cell>Person 5</cell>
                <cell>Sample Mean</cell>
            </row>
            <row><cell>Sample 1</cell><cell>90</cell><cell>82</cell><cell>94</cell><cell>99</cell><cell>110</cell><cell>95.0</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 2</cell><cell>78</cell><cell>88</cell><cell>111</cell><cell>111</cell><cell>117</cell><cell>101.0</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 3</cell><cell>111</cell><cell>122</cell><cell>91</cell><cell>98</cell><cell>86</cell><cell>101.6</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 4</cell><cell>98</cell><cell>96</cell><cell>119</cell><cell>99</cell><cell>107</cell><cell>103.8</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 5</cell><cell>105</cell><cell>113</cell><cell>103</cell><cell>103</cell><cell>98</cell><cell>104.4</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 6</cell><cell>81</cell><cell>89</cell><cell>93</cell><cell>85</cell><cell>114</cell><cell>92.4</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 7</cell><cell>100</cell><cell>93</cell><cell>108</cell><cell>98</cell><cell>133</cell><cell>106.4</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 8</cell><cell>107</cell><cell>100</cell><cell>105</cell><cell>117</cell><cell>85</cell><cell>102.8</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 9</cell><cell>86</cell><cell>119</cell><cell>108</cell><cell>73</cell><cell>116</cell><cell>100.4</cell></row>
            <row><cell>Sample 10</cell><cell>95</cell><cell>126</cell><cell>112</cell><cell>120</cell><cell>76</cell><cell>105.8</cell></row>
        </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
        Now suppose this sampling process is repeated thousands of times. Each sample produces a single value—the sample mean. 
        Collecting these sample means produces a new distribution known as the <em>sampling distribution of the mean</em>. 
        This distribution is illustrated in <xref ref="fig-sampdistmean"/>.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-sampdistmean">
        <caption>
            Sampling distribution of the sample mean based on repeated random samples of size <m>N=5</m>. 
            The distribution shows how the sample mean varies from one sample to another, even though every sample is drawn from the same population. 
            The black curve represents the population distribution.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/sampdistmean.png"/>
    </figure>
    <p>
        The sampling distribution of the mean describes the variability of the sample mean across repeated samples of the same size. 
        Although individual sample means differ because of random sampling variation, they tend to cluster around the population mean. 
        Understanding this distribution is fundamental to statistical inference because it forms the basis for estimating population parameters, 
        constructing confidence intervals, and performing hypothesis tests.
    </p>
</subsection>